{{refimprove|date=May 2013}} [[File:Philip Doddridge.jpg|thumb|Philip Doddridge's portrait and his [[Coat of arms]]. The motto in the Coat of arms is ''Dum vivimus vivamus''.]] '''''Dum vivimus vivamus''''' is a Latin phrase that means "While we live, let us live."<ref name="Dictionary.com">{{cite web |title=dum vivimus, vivamus |publisher=Dictionary.com |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/dum+vivimus,+vivamus |accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dum%20vivimus%20vivamus |title=dum vivimus vivamus |publisher=[[Merriam-Webster dictionary]]}}</ref> It is often taken to be an [[Epicureanism|Epicurean]] declaration.<ref name="Dictionary.com"/>
This Latin phrase was the motto of [[Philip Doddridge]]'s coat of arms.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3XUBAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=Philip+Doddridge+motto&source=bl&ots=eAOjny8yzK&sig=EHwcBZjUaKHHH4TLQA7Tq5FbYqs&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ILpxVYr8MMOuswHUkIGoAQ&ved=0CBQQ6AEwADgK Orton, Job, Memoirs of the Life, Character and Writings of the Late Reverend Philip Doddridge, p. 145.]</ref>
== Usage == It serves as the motto for [[Porcellian Club]] at Harvard. [[Emily Dickinson]] used the line in a whimsical [[valentine's Day|valentine]] written to William Howland in 1852 and subsequently published in the ''[[Springfield Daily Republican]]'':<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=odjIKZKYHJQC&pg=PA350&lpg=PA350&dq=Emily+Dickinson+dum+vivimus+vivamus&source=bl&ots=Z4rwLe0osd&sig=21vPd8Dmltmq6hs3pGzWNIVLCf8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=U8FxVZnaK8aqsgHEhYHgBg&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAg Benson Sewall, Richard, The Life of Emily Dickinson, Volumes 1-2, p. 450.]</ref>
<poem> ''[[Sic transit gloria mundi]] ''[[Against Idleness and Mischief|How doth the busy bee]], ''Dum vivimus vivamus, ''I stay my enemy! </poem>
It was also the motto inscribed on the sword of "Oscar" Gordon, the protagonist of [[Robert Heinlein]]'s 1963 book "[[Glory Road]]". And it is the motto of The Knights of Momus, a New Orleans Carnival organization.
