{{redirect|Tacana|the Peruvian region|Tacna Region}} {{Infobox language |name= Tacana |nativename= |states=[[Bolivia]] |region= |ethnicity=5,100 (2004)<ref name=e18/> |speakers=1,800 |date=2004 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Tacanan languages|Tacanan]] |fam2=Araona–Tacanan |fam3=Cavinena–Tacana |fam4=Tacana Proper |iso3=tna |glotto=taca1256 |glottorefname=Tacana }}
'''Tacana''' is a Western [[Tacanan languages|Tacanan]] language spoken by some 1,800 [[Tacana people]] in [[Bolivia]] out of an ethnic population of 5,000. They live in the forest along the [[Beni River|Beni]] and [[Madre de Dios River|Madre de Dios]] rivers. Numerous dialects, now extinct, have been attributed to Tacana: Ayaychuna, Babayana, Chiliuvo, Chivamona, Idiama (Ixiama), Pamaino, Pasaramona, Saparuna, Siliama, Tumupasa (Maracani, "Tupamasa"), Uchupiamona, Yabaypura, and Yubamona (Mason 1950).
