{{Eastern name order|Soros Tivadar}} '''Tivadar Soros'''<ref>The family changed its name in 1936 from Schwartz to Soros, in response to growing [[anti-semitism]] with the rise of [[Fascism]].</ref> ({{lang-eo|Teodoro Ŝvarc}}; born '''Theodor Schwarz'''; [[7 April]] [[1893]] – [[22 February]] [[1968]]) was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] lawyer, author and editor.<ref name="Soros 2011 p. ">{{cite book | last=Soros | first=Tivadar | title=Masquerade: the incredible true story of how George Soros' father outsmarted the Gestapo | publisher=Arcade Pub | location=New York | year=2011 |url=http://www.boomerangbooks.com.au/Masquerade/Tivadar-Soros/book_9781611450248.htm| isbn=978-1-61145-024-8 | page=}}</ref> He is perhaps best known for being the father of businessman, investor, and philanthropist [[George Soros]], and engineer [[Paul Soros]].
Soros fought in [[World War I]] and spent years in a prison camp in [[Siberia]] before escaping. He founded the [[Esperanto]] literary magazine ''[[Literatura Mondo]]'' (Literary World) in 1922 and edited it until 1924. He wrote the short novel ''Modernaj Robinzonoj'' (Modern Robinsons) (1923), and ''Maskerado ĉirkaŭ la morto'' (Masquerade (dance) around death), published 1965, an autobiographical novel about his experience during the [[Nazism|Nazi]] occupation of [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]. ''Maskerado'' has been translated into [[English language|English]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[German language|German]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bibl.u-szeged.hu/bibl/mil/ww2/konyv/tartalom/s/soros_mt1.html|title=SOROS : Álarcban (tartalom)|website=www.bibl.u-szeged.hu}}</ref>
